<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-10-14T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-10-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="765" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d765">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 300.115/10287</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the Consul General at London</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SRP1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Skinner</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-10-14">
                                        <hi rend="italic">October 14, 1916</hi>
                                    </date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>Your October 10. American demand for needles formerly supplied by
                                Germany approximately 5,000,000 needles monthly, consisting of
                                1,000,000 Standard F, 750,000 Standard B, 125,000 Standard F H
                                Special, 2,000,000 Banner, 1,000,000 miscellaneous. In view Foreign
                                Office note September 4 to Embassy, urge that a share of needles now
                                being produced be apportioned to American mills and ascertain from
                                manufacturers prospects of enlarged future production and earliest
                                date on which supplies for export of various classes can be
                                expected.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>